<Document>
<name>Stelvio Pass — SS38</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Stelvio Pass — SS38</h2><p><i>South Tyrol / Lombardy, Italy · SS38, Bormio to Glorenza</i></p><p><b>48 hairpins on the north side, 38 on the south. 2,757 m, the second-highest paved Alpine pass.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>33 km (20 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Late June–early October (closed for snow Nov–May)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Closure dates uncertain each year, cyclists in formation, motorbikes at speed, snow possible in August, no guardrails on some hairpins</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>95</td></tr></table><hr><p>Built by the Habsburgs in 1820–25 to connect Lombardy with the Tyrol over the most direct Alpine line. Engineer Carlo Donegani designed it; the 48 numbered hairpins on the Trafoi (north) side are still close to his original alignment. Top Gear's Jeremy Clarkson called it 'the greatest driving road in the world' in 2008, which has cursed it with traffic ever since. Cyclists outnumber cars in summer. Best in early morning, weekday, June or October — when snow has melted but tour buses haven't arrived. Stop at the summit café for a Bombardino (eggnog with brandy).</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Bagni Vecchi</b> — 1839 spa terraces built into the cliff face above Bormio. Roman-era bath complex; outdoor pools steam against the snow.</li><li><b>Passo dello Stelvio summit</b> — 2,757 m. Café, monument to engineer Donegani, language line: Italian/German changes here. Toilets queue is real.</li><li><b>Hairpin 48 viewpoint</b> — Pull off at the top of the Trafoi descent. Stack of switchbacks visible spiraling away — the photo of the Stelvio.</li><li><b>Trafoi WWI museum</b> — Above Trafoi village, ruins of the high-altitude Italian/Austrian front line (1915–18). Open trenches at 2,500 m.</li><li><b>Glorenza / Glurns</b> — Tiny intact medieval walled town (population ~900). One of the smallest cities in Europe, with three full city gates and 14th-century walls.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
